article.headline: LOS ANGELES 66, SAN ANTONIO 61
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- When one of Los Angeles' star players went
down with an injury, Lisa Leslie rose up and took the Sparks to
another victory.

Leslie had 18 points and 10 rebounds Friday night, giving Los
Angeles a season-high five-game winning streak with a 66-61 victory
over the San Antonio Silver Stars.

The Sparks also got 17 points from Mwadi Mabika and Tamika
Whitmore added 10. Nikki Teasley had eight assists.

"I thought tonight was a big win for us, it was a good team
effort, but losing DeLisha (Milton-Jones) is a big blow to the
whole team" said Leslie. "They outplayed us in the first half and
we really had to fight to match their intensity in the second
half."

Olympian Delisha Milton-Jones, playing with an injured right
knee ligament, left the court at halftime assisted by her
teammates. She was on a fast break when she fell under the basket,
clutching her knee. She did not return in the second half and will
travel with the Sparks to Houston, and will be re-evaluated Monday
in Los Angeles.

"It's just unfortunate," said Sparks coach Michael Cooper.
"The last time we played them they had Marie Ferdinand go down and
now tonight it was like it was our turn. But that is part of the
game."

Los Angeles trailed by as many as seven points late in the
second half. It took the lead when Mabika hit a 3-pointer with 1:53
on the clock, making it 57-55. Mabika had 14 of her 17 points in
the second half, and was 2-of-3 from behind the 3-point line.

San Antonio, which lost its fourth straight, was led by LaToya
Thomas, who tied a season high in points with 19. Agnieszka
Bibrzycka, starting in place of injured Ferdinand, had 14, while
Tai Dillard had a career-high 11, going 5-for-5 from the field.

Ferdinand, the Silver Stars' leading scorer, is out for the
season with a dislocated right elbow. She hurt it in last Friday's
overtime loss to the Sparks.

"We played hard, made some big shots and had the crowd into
it," said San Antonio head coach Dee Brown. "I'm proud of
everybody. In a system like this, when someone goes down, it's
great to have others step up."

San Antonio had built a 25-18 lead on a 9-0 run before Leslie
answered with back-to-back baskets to end the first half.
